nt a larger portion of Space revenue going forward due to long-term government contracts. \n\n**3. Seasonality Factors or One-Time Items Affecting Q1 2026**\nThe text does not explicitly mention "seasonality" or label specific events as "one-time items." However, it highlights several period-specific timing factors and non-recurring operational impacts affecting Q1 2026:\n*   **Timing of Government Contracts:** The Space segment experienced a $246 million revenue decrease in Q1 2026, driven by lower Launch Services missions and the "timing of work for government contracts." Management notes that Space revenue will vary from period to period based on the mix of launches.\n*   **Accelerated Starship R&D:** The Space segment\'s operating loss and EBITDA were negatively impacted by an accelerated investment of $930 million in R&D for the next-generation Starship launch vehicle and related facilities.\n*   **AI Infrastructure Expansion:** The AI segment saw a massive $1,471 million increase in R&D expenses driven by the depreciation of GPU hardware and cloud computing/data center infrastructure costs resulting from AI data center expansions.\n*   **Anomalies:** The text notes that the Space segment\'s "impairment" line includes losses on fixed assets due to anomalies on flight vehicles and launch sites that occur outside normal business operations, though specific Q1 2026 anomaly figures are not detailed in the excerpts.',
