    tool_call=ToolCall(
        id='call_3f017dd6d7fa472699f4b596',
        call_id=None,
        name='retrieve_information',
        args='{"prompt":"In {{spacex_s1}}, describe the relationship between the AI segment and orbital launch capacity. Does SpaceX plan to deploy AI compute satellites? When? How will kilograms delivered to orbit translate into AI segment revenue in the future?"}',
        parsed_args={
            'prompt': 'In {{spacex_s1}}, describe the relationship between the AI segment and orbital launch capacity. Does SpaceX plan to deploy AI compute satellites? When? How will kilograms delivered to orbit translate into AI segment revenue in the future?'
        }
    ),
    tool_output=ToolOutput(
        output='Based on the provided S-1 preamble chunks, here is the relationship between SpaceX\'s AI segment and its orbital launch capacity, including deployment plans and the translation of mass-to-orbit into future revenue:\n\n**Does SpaceX plan to deploy AI compute satellites?**\nYes. SpaceX plans to leverage its aerospace manufacturing and launch capabilities to build a massive, scalable orbital AI compute network. The company is designing next-generation, high-performance AI compute satellites built for high volume, low cost, and long-duration operation in space. These satellites will form modular "orbital AI compute shells" or data centers, powered by solar energy and interconnected using Starlink\'s mesh network of inter-satellite lasers. \n\n**When?**\nSpaceX expects to begin deploying its orbital AI compute satellites **as early as 2028**. By the end of the decade, the company intends to deploy the first modular orbital AI compute shells and begin monetizing the capacity.\n\n**How will kilograms delivered to orbit translate into AI segment revenue in the future?**\nThe translation of launch capacity (kilograms/metric tons delivered to orbit) into AI segment revenue relies on a vertically integrated strategy where mass becomes compute power, and compute power is monetized as a service. Here is how the conversion works based on the text:\n\n1. **Launch Capacity Allocation:** The Space segment will allocate a significant amount of its launch capacity to the AI segment in the future (similar to how it currently allocates capacity to the Connectivity segment for Starlink). While this internal allocation means the Space segment won\'t recognize revenue for those launches, it provides the foundational infrastructure for the AI segment to generate revenue.\n2. **Mass-to-Compute Conversion:** SpaceX translates mass directly into compute capacity. Early satellites are expected to generate **100 kilowatts of compute power per metric ton**. \n3. **Scaling to Gigawatts:** Using Starship V3 (designed to carry 100 metric tons to orbit per reusable flight) and scaling to thousands of launches per year, SpaceX aims to transport approximately **one million metric tons to orbit annually**. At 100 kilowatts per metric ton, this translates to **100 gigawatts of AI compute capacity deployed per year**.\n4. **Monetization:** Once the mass is converted into operational orbital compute capacity, the AI segment will monetize it in two primary ways:\n   * **Sale of AI Compute:** Selling high-performance compute capacity to a limited number of third-party customers to run energy-intensive AI workloads, such as inference demand.\n   * **Sale of AI Software:** Utilizing the compute capacity to power its own frontier AI models and selling AI software applications to consumer and enterprise customers.\n\nUltimately, SpaceX believes that by using its reusable rockets to launch mass at scale and its satellite manufacturing to turn that mass into solar-powered compute nodes, it can deliver AI compute over time at a fundamentally lower cost structure than is possible on Earth, driving the AI segment\'s future economic returns.',
        error=None,
        metadata=None,
        done=False,
        success=True
    ),
    duration_seconds=27.226,
    error=None,
    success=True
)
