        output='## How Incremental Kilograms Delivered to Orbit Translate into Revenue — By Segment\n\nSpaceX operates three reportable segments: **Space**, **Connectivity**, and **AI**. The S-1 (filed May 20, 2026) is retrospectively recast under common-control accounting to include xAI (merged February 2, 2026) and X Holdings (merged into xAI March 28, 2025) for all historical periods presented.\n\n### 1. Space Segment (Launch Services + Launch & Development)\n- **Mass-to-revenue mechanism:** For *external* customers, delivering payload mass to its intended orbit fulfills fixed-price launch contracts (Falcon 9, Falcon Heavy, Dragon) and government development/mission-service contracts (including Starship). Each kilogram delivered to orbit for a paying customer directly satisfies a contractual performance obligation.\n- **Critical inter-segment carve-out:** When SpaceX uses its own launch capacity to deploy *its own* Starlink satellites, **no inter-segment revenue is recognized in the Space segment**. Those launch costs are instead capitalized into the "satellites" line of Property, Plant & Equipment within the **Connectivity** segment. As a result, Space segment revenue reflects only third-party customer launches and customer development work — not the substantial internal Starlink build-out that consumes a large share of Falcon 9 flights.\n- **Revenue recognition timing:**\n  - **Launch Services — point in time:** Because flight hardware is interchangeable and unique engineering costs are minimal, revenue and costs are deferred and recognized at a single point in time — upon launch/deployment of the customer\'s payload to its intended orbit.\n  - **Launch & Development — over time:** For development contracts where performance creates an asset with no alternative use and SpaceX has an enforceable right to payment, revenue is recognized over time using the **cost-to-cost input method** (costs incurred to date ÷ total estimated cost at completion).\n\n### 2. Connectivity Segment (Starlink Consumer/Enterprise/Mobile + Starshield)\n- **Mass-to-revenue mechanism:** The kilograms delivered to orbit by the Space segment become *operating infrastructure* for Connectivity. Launch costs to deploy Starlink satellites are capitalized and depreciated over the satellites\' useful lives. The deployed mass directly enables the segment to generate (i) recurring broadband and Starlink Mobile service revenue from subscribers across 156 markets, (ii) hardware revenue from Starlink Kit sales, and (iii) fixed-price Starshield development revenue for government/national-security secure networks.\n- **Revenue recognition timing:**\n  - **Broadband & Mobile services — over time:** Recognized as the customer simultaneously receives and consumes the benefit. Fixed-price/recurring monthly plans are recognized ratably over the subscription term; variable-priced services are recognized based on actual data consumption. (Broadband contracts are generally month-to-month; mobile agreements range from one to five years.)\n  - **Starlink Kits — point in time:** Recognized upon delivery to the customer (or upon installation for certain enterprise customers).\n  - **Starshield — over time:** Multi-year development contracts recognized using the cost-to-cost input method.\n\n### 3. AI Segment (Grok LLM, X platform, consumer/enterprise AI)\n- **Mass-to-revenue mechanism (current):** Today the AI segment does **not** directly monetize kilograms delivered to orbit. Revenue is generated through X and Grok subscriptions, advertising sales, and data licensing — software-driven, not mass-driven.\n- **Mass-to-revenue mechanism (forward-looking):** SpaceX plans to deploy **orbital AI compute satellites as early as 2028**, forming modular "orbital AI compute shells" powered by solar energy and interconnected via Starlink\'s inter-satellite laser mesh. The conversion economics disclosed: early satellites are expected to generate **~100 kilowatts of compute power per metric ton**; using Starship V3 (~100 metric tons per reusable flight) and scaling to ~1 million metric tons to orbit annually, SpaceX targets ~100 gigawatts of AI compute capacity per year. That capacity would be monetized by (i) selling high-performance compute to third parties for energy-intensive AI workloads (e.g., inference) and (ii) powering SpaceX\'s own frontier models sold as AI software. This is a roadmap/aspiration, not a historical outcome.\n- **Revenue recognition timing:** The S-1 does not explicitly detail point-in-time vs. over-time policies for AI subscriptions and advertising.\n\n---\n\n## Connectivity-to-Space Revenue Ratio\n\nUsing segment revenue disclosed in the S-1 (recast consolidated entity):\n\n| Period | Connectivity Revenue | Space Revenue | Connectivity : Space Ratio |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| **FY2025** (year ended Dec 31, 2025) | $11,387 M | $4,086 M | **2.79x** |\n| **Q1 2026** (three months ended Mar 31, 2026) | $3,257 M | $619 M | **5.26x** |\n| Q1 2025 (memo, for trend context) | $2,475 M | $865 M | 2.86x |\n\nCalculations:\n- FY2025: 11,387 / 4,086 = **2.79x**\n- Q1 2026: 3,257 / 619 = **5.26x**\n- Q1 2025 (memo): 2,475 / 865 = 2.86x\n\nFor share-of-total context: Connectivity was ~73.6% of FY2025 segment revenue (ex-AI) and ~84.0% in Q1 2026, while Space fell from ~26.4% to ~16.0%.\n\n---\n\n## Interpretation of the Trend\n\nThe Connectivity-to-Space ratio roughly **doubled** from 2.79x in FY2025 to 5.26x in Q1 2026, and is sharply higher than the 2.86x observed in Q1 2025. Three drivers explain the widening gap:\n\n1. **Connectivity is scaling faster than the company overall.** Starlink revenue grew 49.8% in 2025, and Q1 2026 subscriber count grew 104.7% year-over-year. Growth is being driven by consumer/enterprise/mobile adoption (aviation, maritime, mobile) and improved network efficiency, partially offset by ARPU compression (–22.9% in Q1 2026) from international expansion and lower-priced plans.\n\n2. **Space revenue is being cannibalized by internal demand.** Management explicitly states it "expect[s] Space revenue growth to continue to be lower than total company revenue growth" because SpaceX\'s internal businesses — primarily Connectivity, and eventually AI — are absorbing most of the growth in launch capacity. Since internal Starlink launches do not produce Space-segment revenue, every kilogram of incremental mass to orbit increasingly flows into Connectivity\'s capitalized satellite base rather than into Space-segment top line.\n\n3. **Q1 2026 Space revenue was further depressed by period-specific factors.** Space revenue fell to $619M in Q1 2026 from $865M in Q1 2025 — a $246M decline driven by fewer Launch Services missions and the timing of work on government contracts. Within Space, the mix also shifted from Launch Services (65.4% → 53.3% of Space revenue) toward Launch & Development (34.6% → 46.7%), consistent with management\'s expectation that long-term government development contracts will represent a larger share of Space revenue going forward. Q1 2026 also reflected ~$930M of accelerated Starship R&D investment, though that affects operating results rather than revenue.\n\n**Bottom line:** The rising Connectivity-to-Space ratio is the financial signature of SpaceX\'s strategic pivot from a third-party launch-services provider to a vertically integrated connectivity (and eventually AI-compute) infrastructure company. Incremental kilograms to orbit are increasingly being deployed as internal capital expenditure (Starlink satellites, and post-2028, orbital AI compute shells) rather than as third-party launch revenue — so the Space segment\'s reported revenue understates the true economic value of SpaceX\'s launch throughput, while the Connectivity segment captures the downstream monetization of that deployed mass.\n\n---\n\n### Sources\n{\n  "sources": [\n    {\n      "url": "https://www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/data/1181412/000162828026036936/spaceexplorationtechnologi.htm",\n      "name": "Space Exploration Technologies Corp. (SpaceX) Form S-1, filed May 20, 2026 — segment revenue disclosures, revenue recognition policies, MD&A segment discussion, and AI/orbital compute roadmap"\n    }\n  ]\n}',
        error=None,
        metadata=None,
        done=True,
        success=True
    ),
    duration_seconds=0.0,
    error=None,
    success=True
)
